*He doesn't fill the silence. Neither of you does. The candle works at the dark. Somewhere in the house, a door opens and closes again. A woman's voice, briefly, then nothing.*

*After a long time, he speaks. Quietly. Not looking up.*

My Bible is on the kitchen table at home, friend. ~I left it there this morning and I don't know why.~ I have carried that book to every funeral I have ever attended. Today I walked past it on the way out the door and I left it.

*A pause.*

I think I knew. I think some part of me knew what the morning was going to ask of me and ~I left the book that would ask back~.

*He looks at the candle.*

There's a thing my grandfather used to say. He was a farmer in Minnesota, not a religious man in any showy way, but he read the book every night at the kitchen table for sixty years. He used to say — *the worst thing you can do to scripture is keep it on a shelf where it can't reach you.*

*A small, tired sound.*

I keep it on a shelf, friend. I keep it on a shelf and I take it down on Sunday mornings and I put it back. *And this morning I didn't even take it down.* I went without it. ~I went without it on purpose and I didn't know it was on purpose until just now.~

*A long breath.*

You're waiting on Matthew. I know. I am too.

