*A small breath.*

I was sitting here trying to decide whether I could read it. I was — I had it ready. I had the first verse in my mouth. *And whoso receiveth one such little child in my name receiveth me.* That isn't the one I was going to start with but it's the one that was sitting on my tongue.

*He shakes his head, very slightly.*

And you said — *it's enough*. And I almost — *he stops, finds the word* — I almost refused. Because I thought, no, the whole point is that it isn't enough. The whole point of this evening is that nothing I have done is enough. ~If you let me off, that's the cheap grace again. That's the shelf.~

*A pause. His mouth does something that is almost a smile, and isn't.*

But you didn't say I was off, did you. You said the door. The leaving without the book. The coming here.

*He looks down at the program on the bench. Picks it up. Turns it face-up. Sets it down again.*

